The same difficulty meets the editor. In controverting the positions of a work which for more than a century and a half has enjoyed the sanction of the Universsty, somewhat more of the verecunde dissentio is becoming than can always bc comprised within the necessary limits of a foot—note. The further discussion of such points in an Appendix has iu some instances unavoidably produced a certain amount of repetition. This however, though injurious to the form of the work, will, it is hoped, not render it the less serviceable to that not in- considerable class of students οἷς οὐδὲ τςὶς λέγοντες ἐξικνούμεθα.

Α few passages omitted iu recent editions of the Compendium have been restored in the present. This, however, has been done but sparingly. An account of the Arbor Porphyricma has been trans- ferred to the first chapter from its original place in the Penus Logica. The obvious utility of the insertion will, it is hoped, warrant the liberty iu this single instance taken with the text.
